comment_data.body: Why `float`? The [calculations in CPython](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/1b97b9b0ad9a2ff8eb5c8f2e2e7c2aec1d13a330/Modules/_datetimemodule.c#L1759) are done in full `PyLong / C double` accuracy. I don't see why we should diverge from that.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -216,3 +210,12 @@ cdef inline int timedelta_seconds(object o):
 # Get microseconds of timedelta
 cdef inline int timedelta_microseconds(object o):
     return (<PyDateTime_Delta*>o).microseconds
+
+cdef inline double total_seconds(timedelta obj):
+    # Mirrors the timedelta.total_seconds method
+    cdef:
+        float days, seconds, micros

comment_data.body:
> Why float?

No reason, will update.

comment_data.body:
I think we should still add a comment that this uses more floating point operations and thus is not guaranteed to give the same result. (It probably does for reasonable time ranges, though.)
```suggestion
    # Mirrors the "timedelta.total_seconds()" method.
    # Note that this implementation is not guaranteed to give *exactly* the same
    # result as the original method, due to potential differences in floating point rounding.
```

 cdef inline int timedelta_microseconds(object o):

+
+cdef inline double total_seconds(timedelta obj):
+    # Mirrors the timedelta.total_seconds method

comment_data.body:
Not a good idea. This will enforce type checks on caller side if the type is not known, which will either reduce the performance or make users uglify their input with type casts.

These are clearly macros, designed for speed. Let it crash if users misapply them.
